  "summary": "Hercule Poirot reveals that Franklin Clarke is the serial killer behind the ABC murders. Poirot explains that Clarke intentionally misdelivered the third letter to him by using a clever address error—\"White Harbor - White Horse\"—to ensure a private detective would receive it rather than the police. This allowed Clarke to escape the crime scene before the police could investigate. Clarke’s motive was to kill his brother, but he staged a third murder at Tancaster to prevent suspicion of an abrupt end to the case.\n\nTo frame Alexander Bonaparte Cast, Clarke staged a crime at a cinema. He stabbed a random man in the dark, placed the ABC book on the victim, and then bumped into Cast, wiping the knife on Cast's sleeve and planting it in his pocket. Due to Cast's epilepsy and memory gaps, Cast believed he had committed the murders himself. Poirot explains that he knew Cast was innocent and that Clarke had used a weighted club for the Andover and Cheltenham murders. Evidence against Clarke included witness identifications in Bexhill and, most decisively, Clarke's fingerprints on Cast's typewriter.\n\nWhen confronted, Clarke attempted suicide with a revolver, but Poirot's valet had previously pickpocketed the gun and removed the bullets. Clarke is arrested by Scotland Yard detectives. In the aftermath, Poirot explains his methods to Hastings, admitting that the fingerprint evidence was a bluff to break Clarke's composure. Later, Cast visits the group, now a celebrity due to the case, and expresses his intent to sell his story to the newspapers.",
